title: For Sale:  LLama .38 Special revolver (1950s quality)
postcontent: Excellent condition.  I'm a private collector and, as part of a multi-gun lot in a recent auction, picked up an excellent .38 Special revolver.  It doesn’t fit in with the rest of my collection, so I’m offering it for sale, but not before testing it thoroughly at my local range. It is in great shape; is spot-on accurate; and will be an excellent, low-cost self-defense or carry gun for a new owner.  The revolver is a Llama Ruby Extra, made in the 1960s in Spain by the Llama-Gabilondo y Cia company to compete globally with Smith & Wesson’s Model 10 as a police issue sidearm.  This Llama has features like a grooved backstrap for a better grip and a grooved top strap to cut down on haze in the sight radius that make is actually nicer than the Smith & Wesson Model 10.  The Llama Ruby Extra sold well to police departments in South America and the Philippines but this one must have been shipped directly to the US as it is not import-marked.  The bore/lands/grooves are in great condition and the gun has just a trace of finish wear at the muzzle, so it seems to have spent more time in a sock drawer than a holster.  I'd prefer a face to face sale in the Glenview area.  You'll need a) to have a valid FOID card and drivers license with matching addresses, b) to sign a bill of sale c) to have the patience for a 72 hour waiting period [no exceptions], and have $245 cash or check. title: For Sale:  High Quality Custom Built Piston AR 5.56/.223
postcontent:
Most likely soon to be banned. This one is definitely not one of the "cookie-cutter" AR's you will find at any of the big name stores around that are selling for $1000 and up. And chances are you will be on a list to get one if you can find one of those anymore.

When I started this project I did a lot of research and ordered every part from quality manufacturers.
It's a high quality precision rifle on an AR platform. I would put it up against any other AR out there. I have shot Sub-MOA groups consistently out to 300 yards.
Here is the break down:
-Spikes Tactical receiver
-Rock River Arms 2-stage trigger and lower parts kit
-Rock River Arms buffer and spring
-Rock River Arms rubber molded grip
-BCM Mod 4 charging handle
-16" 1:8 twist Nordic Match Grade Stainless Heavy Barrel w/ mid-length gas port (Properly broken in with one shot and clean method)
-Adams Arms mid-length adjustable gas/piston system (Perfect set-up for running suppressed)
-Midwest Industries Free floated 2 piece hand guard w/ rail covers
-Midwest Industries Flash suppressor/muzzle break
-Mako GL-shock adjustable butt stock
-Magpul Back Up Sights included
-Also includes tactical rifle bag
-(3) 20- round mags (will also likely be banned soon)

title: For Sale:  Type Chinese Red Army Tokarev pistol
postcontent: I'm a private collector and, as part of a multi-gun lot in a recent auction, picked up an excellent Type 54 semiauto pistol in 7.62 x 25 Tokarev.  .  It shows no wear from carry or use but doesn’t fit in with the rest of my collection, so I’m offering it for sale.  This gun was made in the 1950’s by the state armory in the Peoples Republic of China for the Red Army.  It is a faithful copy of the Tokarev pistol designed by China’s then-ally, the USSR, with exception of an added safety to allow cocked-and-locked carry (never carry an original design Russian Tokarev with a round in the chamber).  This gun is lightweight and well-balanced.  I’ve not fired this gun, but the ammunition choices are said to be varied and even quite fun!  Conventional 7.62 x 25 ammo is available from most of the major internet ammo sellers.  But you can also get green or red tracer ammo for low-light shooting.  Although the Type 54 is dated by contemporary military standards, this is said to be the most popular handgun among organized crime figures in Asia as the ammo available overseas is hot enough to defeat body armor.  I'd prefer a face to face sale in the Glenview area. This is a rare Bulgarian Arsenal SLR95 AK that was imported before the '99 import ban which required 922(r) compliance (a minimum proportion of US made parts).  It was imported with a plastic sporter thumbhole stock and a dust cover witha  picatinny rail on it (see top picture).  Lower pics are the current configuration.

I've also put a Krebs Custom safety lever that has the bolt hold open notch and the lever on it so you can use your finger and keep your hand on the grip.

This gun, like current edition Bulgarian Arsenal SLRs (101) are probably the best Aks out there, better than the Russian ones.  Unlike the current SLRs, this one was shipped from the factory in Bulgaria fully assembled by the experts using all matching parts and perfect assembly...unlike current ones reassembled here by various US importers.  Current SLRs are $1k (http://www.k-var.com/shop/SLR-101S.html).  The value of this gun is at least between 1200-1500 BEFORE the panic.  I don't think $2000 is too much to ask, but I am negotiable.  

Gun comes with 7 clean, new Bulgarian mags (the good kind with the rib on the back) that could easily go for $50 a piece in todays market.  Also with the gun and mags is 300 rounds of ammo.
